I asked my seven-year-old son what he thought of THE ADAM PROJECT, and he said the time travel. “If I met my future self, I’d want him to tell me how many Pokemon cards I have in the future. I hope a lot more than I do now” So, he definitely has his priorities figured out.

Special thanks to @VancityReynolds for nailing that bar scene with his "mom". I know this is a family film, fun and games and farting bullet wounds, but those three minutes were some of the most cathartic I've experienced since my own mother died.

My son and I had a blast watching THE ADAM PROJECT together. He enjoyed the farting bullet wound jokes, while I found myself repeatedly devastated by the well-executed fantasy of being able to go back in time to fix what went wrong between you and your dead parents.

Anyways, check out @JamesGunn's PEACEMAKER. It's eight quick episodes of joyous filmmaking, heart and muscles and entrails and laughs, and, because Gunn's involved, one hell of a soundtrack. In these dark, shitty times, you can't really ask for more.

I have to point out @freddiestroma's portrayal of Vigilante, too. Freddie hung on my sofa a few times for movie marathons back in the day when I was a Los Angeleno. I'm so glad the rest of the world has caught on to how goddamn talented he is.

Amongst many great scenes John Cena knocks out of the park, there is one in Episode 6 of PEACEMAKER, where he (really) plays an aching piano cover of Motley Crue’s “Home Sweet Home” that will devastate you. Gunn talks about it here: https://t.co/QD2kzPWtHN

Peacemaker was a bit of a punchline in #THESUICIDESQUAD, a character who reminded me of many people I grew up around. But Gunn uses his new series to dissect that toxic, unthinking masculinity and uber-patriotism and present him instead as a portrait of trauma and recovery.

.@JamesGunn  strikes such a marvelous tone in his films and, now, TV. #PEACEMAKER is a violent, vulgar, hilarious super-hero romp full of gore, more F-bombs than a Tarantino flick, and Aquaman fish-banging jokes. But it’s also buoyant with heart that genuinely moves you.

Thus concludes, the tragic tale of Kay Kendall. Anyways, LES GIRLS is a fun enough film, especially its conceit. She’s wonderful in it. 12/ https://t.co/6CRF198jnh

After Kendall’s death, Harrison presumed he would promptly remarry the ex-wife he still very much loved, too. Except Palmer had fallen in love with her boy toy (perfectly named Carlos) by now, too, and decided to marry him instead. 11/

Kendall tragically died at 32, still ignorant of the fact that she had leukemia or that her husband spent their marriage lying to her about it, theoretically so she could go on enjoying what life she had left. This sounds unbelievably romantic, but is really horrifying. 10/ https://t.co/zAYMnnHqVh

I think it’s fair to say Palmer is easily the most understanding wife in history because the plan also involved Harrison remarrying Palmer once Kendall passed away. It’s also possible Palmer didn’t care so much because she had her own lover on the side. 9/

Harrison, devastated that Kendall was going to die, devised a plan with Palmer: he would divorce her, marry Kendall, and provide for her care as she died – WITHOUT EVER TELLING HER SHE WAS DYING. Kendall just thought she had an iron deficiency. 8/ https://t.co/3OWdxXrqUK

This is because Kendall’s doctor had confided in Harrison that Kendall was dying of myeloid leukemia. The thing is, HE NEVER TOLD KENDALL SHE WAS DYING. He told Kendall’s married lover instead. Because in the 1950s, apparently that’s what you did. 7/

Harrison was married to actress Lilli Palmer at the time, a marriage that was apparently still going well. Except for the infidelity, of course. Palmer would learn about this when Harrison came to her and basically said, “Look, I’m cheating on you…but the woman is dying.” 6/

Rewind. After years of epic affairs with Europe’s most desirable bachelors – including Charlie Chaplin’s son, a Swedish prince, the Sainsbury’s heir, and (allegedly) the UK’s Prince Philip – Kendall fell in love with actor Rex Harrison on the set of THE CONSTANT HUSBAND. 5/ https://t.co/KJPyxYmQ4i
This might sound like Kendall decided to go out fighting and living her best life right up until the end, but the reality is she had no idea what was happening to her. 4/
Kendall was only 31 at the time LES GIRLS was produced. She appeared so gaunt and…aged…in the part because she was dying of leukemia. 3/

As my wife and I watched LES GIRLS, we tried to guess the ages of the actresses. In the 50s, 20-something women were regularly cast as 30 and 40-something women were cast as mothers of the male lead. We guessed Kendall was in her 40s. Wikipedia soon revealed how wrong we were. 2/ https://t.co/4ZpcaXZcOh

Last night, I watched LES GIRLS (1957), a mediocre Cole Porter musical starring Gene Kelly as the leader of a dance troupe he uses to find girlfriends. In doing so, I learned the tragic and completely bonkers tale of star Kay Kendall. It’s almost too much to believe. 1/ https://t.co/1vzySQ6CKX

In other words: DUNE, co-written by @jonspaihts, Denis Villeneuve, and Eric Roth, is a master class in how to adapt a novel for screen. As a fan of the novel, I am still in awe of how well it all worked.

Much of DUNE’s success as a film is certainly attributable to Villeneuve’s hypnotic, unsettling direction – an almost Kubrickian take on the space epic – but none of that would have mattered without the extraordinary narrative feat that its screenplay pulls off.
The result is a laser-focused screenplay that manages what I once thought was impossible: to economically tell the story of DUNE in such a way that EVERYONE can follow it and be moved by it.

Fans of the novel see these processes at work on-screen, and fill in the blanks for themselves. But everyone else – such as my wife who had never read DUNE – aren’t burdened with details that, as it turns out, aren’t necessary to understand the emotional heart of the story.

When I say the script cuts these other details out, it doesn’t actually disregard the world-building behind them. It’s all there on-screen, but there isn’t a single mention of mentats and the Butlerian Jihad that made them necessary, or even how the Navigators bend space.

The script for DUNE (2021), co-written by @jonspaihts (whom I’m friendly with and a great fan of), director Villeneuve, and Eric Roth, solves these problems with one graceful solution: it cuts out everything irrelevant to telling and understanding the Atreides family’s story.

Is DIAMOND DOGS David Bowie’s greatest album? That’s a wholly subjective question, but it’s easily one his most metatextually complex works and, in my opinion, a work of postmodern rock genius. Give it a go on vinyl if you can; you won't regret it. 11/11

Most artists choose to have these conversations with audiences, making them active participants in the experience – and that’s certainly happening here – but Bowie’s focus seems to primarily be on himself. In other words, DIAMOND DOGS is one of his most personal albums. 10/11

I also think DIAMOND DOGS is Bowie having a conversation with himself about what his art means to him, how scared he is of it and fame, the dissonance between the rock star David Bowie and the Brixton lad named David Jones. 9/11 https://t.co/rSpkI7j33X
In this regard, you can look at DIAMOND DOGS as a kind of confession by Bowie to all the murders of his previous personas and all the murders still to come. But… 8/11

Smarter people than I have tackled the genius of this album, but, for me, I think I’m most fascinated by how DIAMOND DOGS appears to be about a rock star so anxious about his influence that he regularly creates identities only to kill them before they get too godlike. 7/11 https://t.co/QKnmaYDnNL

Consider the lyrics to DIAMOND DOG’s “Big Brother” after Bowie has already lyrically conflated the rock star with Orwell’s Big Brother (DIAMOND DOGS began life as an early attempt to turn 1984 into a musical): 5/11

Bowie even conflates fascism with the power rock stars hold over audiences. For example, “ROCK ‘N’ ROLL WITH ME” (one of my favorite songs on the album) is a ballad between a musical dictator and his followers. It *feels* like a music video directed by Leni Riefenstahl. 4/11 https://t.co/zG8flxinlb

The result of this mash-up is a raw, dark, and apocalyptic musical landscape accompanied by puzzle-like lyrics that, only upon obsessive listening, begin to assemble into a musical treatise against fascism and, in particular, Bowie’s fear of the rock star (himself). 3/11

More than any of Bowie’s other albums, I find myself returning to DIAMOND DOGS and its mash-up of Bowie’s glam theatricality, George Orwell’s novel 1984, and a cut-up narrative style familiar to William Burroughs fans. 2/11

I’ve linked to @mangiotto here because I admire and respect him and, as a deep thinker, I expect he is very used to people having different opinions than his. This debate is an important one to me, which is the only reason I am sharing my opinion on the matter here.

We might not like the experience, we might not like what it says about the world or even us as individuals, but the experience is all we are entitled to when we show up to museums or buy books or buy film tickets, etc.

I’d argue this isn’t arrogance, but rather a refusal to accept that audiences are entitled to anything from the artist except an experience specifically curated from the artist’s POV. It is the artist speaking their “truth” (a term I hate, sorry).

Artists create art, and sometimes that art challenges their audiences, and sometimes their audiences are even put in the crosshairs to make an ideological point. See Banksy’s "Girl With Balloon”. https://t.co/xSEU1xvpYh.

This is because paradigms typically inform identity and identities don’t like to be challenged. Many people can’t even denounce personal heroes revealed to be truly horrible because to do so is akin to denouncing themselves. See Trump’s supporters or Bill Cosby’s defenders.

Historically speaking, this has almost always resulted in critics and the influential condemning the new for condemning the old. The same applies to other arenas of thought, like the sciences (i.e., Copernicus was destroyed for stating the obvious).

I struggle with this take from Walter (a THREAD). All art that challenges paradigms must in some way confront and condemn the previous paradigm...even if the previous paradigm was created by the same artist. https://t.co/vGyoscyXwP
